segments.text: But there's no way of explaining the Aggie spirit that I know of.
You have to.
I know when I went home at Christmas, and I just laughingly told them about the hazing, some of it.
I didn't tell them all of it.
They didn't want me to go back to A&M, these people I had been working for.
That was home to me from then on.
No, they wanted me to go to University of Texas.
But no way was I going to the SIPP school by then, because I had been indoctrinated at A&M.
I was an Aggie.
And just like this little fella here, he became an MD, and he's still practicing in Mount Pleasant, Texas.
Little William Taylor, yeah.
The others are dead.
Nice little bill.
So did you first come in 1920?
Fall of 1924.
Okay.
And then you received your degree in 1931, didn't you?
Well, I changed over to biology, as I said.
And then I took pre-med.
And in 1927, I went to Galveston Medical School.
Oh, you did?
I was there a year.
And in the first month of June, I was at home.
I broke down with tuberculosis.
In fact, I had had TB here at A&M.
I know because I had a pulmonary hemorrhage one night there in the dormitory.
and went over to the college hospital.
This is an indictment of our college hospital as it was.
And old Arsocks, who was the head nurse, didn't want to let me in because it was after hours.
They closed it at 9 o'clock.
No matter if you had tuberculosis or not.
I was spitting out blood.
Really?
I was having a pulmonary hemorrhage.
And I had pleurisy so badly that I could hardly breathe.
So she finally let me in and gave me a bed.
The next morning, the doctor had me get up and come around to his office instead of coming to my bed.
Of course, I didn't know what was wrong with me at that time.
But he examined me and said there was a little place up in my nasal cavity that was
raw and was bleeding and it was running down in my throat and I was spitting it up.
I said, well I don't know about that because I had my head over like this between my knees almost and I spat blood out on the piece of paper that I had on the floor.
No blood came out of my nose with my head in that position.
Oh, he says, well, that's what it is.
And so I said, well, what about this pleurisy?
I can hardly breathe.
He says, oh, well, if it gets too bad, come back and I'll strap you down.
So I went ahead.
He wouldn't even give me a military to get me out of revelry, exercises, or cavalry, drill, or anything, saber charges, or anything else.
So I streaked along for several weeks, just a little blood,
But I finally got over it.
I don't know how.
And that came up in later years.
There was a committee investigating the college hospital.
This was during Mr. Gilchrist's time as president.
And so they had a committee over from Scott and White to examine the college hospital.
And of course, they found it A1 because Dr. Marsh, who was the resident physician, had interned at Scott and White.
Sure.
So nothing.
And I had a friend who was externing that year.
He was a medical student in Galveston.
He was externing as an extern in the college hospital.
And they didn't allow him to come back to the hospital that day.
And just only the licensed nurse was there.
And the others, they kept away.

Anyhow, I don't know whether you want to put that in there or not, but anyhow, they had me up and I reported to this committee and all that sort of thing, and they had the investigation and whitewashed the whole thing.
Well, I went to Galveston Medical School in September following that.
And what do you think happened?
You got TB.
I never did recover.
Really?
I never did recover.
I knew there was something wrong with me during the whole year, but then when June came around, I broke down again.
And that time, I went out to Sanatorium, Texas, was admitted out there, and I spent five months out there.
Got an arrested case.
Oh, good.
And by that time, I was out of money, strapped.
We had, my father had sold the lower farm, and I did get my mother's part.
There were five children for that to be divided among.
I got my part from my mother's interest in the place.
And I had that to go on, but that wasn't enough to take me back to medical school.
But that year, I came back to A&M.
I was sitting there on the corner of Old Gathright, the porch on Old Gathright Hall, which has been torn down many years ago.
After I'd registered, I wondered what I was going to do.
Who wants to room with someone who's had tuberculosis?
Well, I just happened to look up about that time, and here came an old boy down Military Walk.
He and I had been at sanatorium together.
Oh, really?
Yeah.
And so I said, hey, come here.
What are you doing?
He said, I just registered.
I'm going to A&M.
I said, well, where are you going to live?
He said, I don't know yet.
I'll have to find a place.
I said, well, wait a minute.
We'll find a place together.
Two old lungers.
So we found a place in Bryant.
So in other words, you didn't live on campus.
No, I didn't.
I couldn't have gone in the dormitory because there was no place for them.
It was all military.
In other words, you didn't have to be in the military, no?
Once you were initiated past the fish, you didn't have to?
Yeah, you had to in those days.
Everybody had to be in the military.
They were all in the military.
So you lived off
campus and then everybody still nevertheless wore that poor uniform.
Well, he and I didn't because we were just classified as day students then.
But if you lived in the dormitory, you were in the military and you wore the uniform and so on.
When I first went to A&M, everybody wore the uniform whether they were crippled or not.
Casual, they lived around over there in either Alpha or Beta Hall, those old halls that were down there where Walton Hall is now.
There were two old southern homes with the big columns in front and so on.
That's where the cosmopolites lived, the foreign students and all the cripples and what have you.
They called them gold breakers and sons of rest and all that sort of thing.
Anyhow.
He and I roomed together, and I went to A&M.
And that was in 1929.
And 1930, he and I were still together.
We got us a room over at Bryan Nursery and Floral Company, fired the boiler, and stemmed flowers, and helped around the place for our room, and boarded next door.
1931, while we lived on the back porch at his mother's home on Texas Avenue in Bryan.
Just the other side of where that hat company is now.
Old two-story house.
Why did you decide to go to veterinary school?
Well, back about 1930, I began taking elective courses in veterinary medicine.
Because you could get bacteriology and physiology and some good courses over there at that time in those areas.
And they would allow you to pick up electives in veterinary medicine.
Because in 1930, they had only one student graduate.
The beginning of the Great Depression.
They were very happy to have people come over so they could keep their courses open.
So 1931, I got my degree in biology.
And I began work on a master's degree in biology.
In 1932, I picked up my first fellowship, $45 a month.
I didn't know if Dr. Ball, who was head of the biology department, had mapped out my work for two years.
And he thought I would have the fellowship both years.
Well, in 1932, it worked nicely.
I had the fellowship, $45 a month.
And I was still doing all my cooking and washing and ironing and everything myself.
time came in 1932 for me to come back to school.
It was in the fall of 32.
And Dr. Ball found out that I couldn't have the fellowship two years in succession.
It was in the fall of 33.
I couldn't have this fellowship two years in succession.
Dr. Morgan, who was dean of the graduate school, said they only had
eight fellowships at A&M, and they had to pass them around.
So I didn't find that out until it was too late for me to do anything else about it.
I didn't have money enough to come back to school.
I worked for the Texas Highway Department that year.
Oh, you did.
$3 and a half a day.
And the little course that I had in plane surveying came in handy.
Because I knew how to set up the transit, the levels, and so on.
I knew what they were doing with points on the tangent and all that business.
I knew what they were doing.
And rainy days, I worked in the office running a planimeter, figuring out cross sections and the amount of dirt removed and so on, what to pay the contractor and what not.
So it worked out very nicely.
I saved my money.
The following year, then I came back to A&M.
I picked up that fellowship again at $45 a month.
But nevertheless, that was still in biology, right?
Still in biology.
This was in bacteriology.
Well, why'd you decide to go into veterinary medicine then?
Well, I graduated.
I got my master's degree in 34 in biology.
I had about half of the course in veterinary medicine worked off as electives.
I see.
So it was a toss-up whether to go for a PhD in bacteriology or should I go ahead and finish veterinary medicine.
I see.
Well, PhD in bacteriology, a dime a dozen.
Oh, they were in the Depression.
Mm-hmm.
Veterinary medicine, to me, was the better of the better choice.
And that's what I took.
So I picked up a fellowship then in pathology.
One of these.
Another $450 deal.
I was still living off the campus and still doing all of my cooking and washing and ironing and what have you.
And still with this same old boy, you and I.
And Brian.
So I had that fellowship two years.
And that took me on through then.
And I graduated in veterinary medicine in August of 36.
And Dr. Marsteller hired me as an instructor for September of 36.
And I began teaching then as an instructor in pathology.
Summers of 37 and the summers of 38, Ruth and I took out, went to Michigan, University of Michigan.
Really?
Took their pathology in medical school.
They would admit a veterinarian.
You had to have a doctor's degree in the medical sciences, either an MD or a DVM or a DDS.
So they would admit you.
Well, could you compare the level of instruction with the University of Michigan with...
with Texas A&M about at that time?
You'd have to go back and look at veterinary school at Texas A&M.
It was created or established in 1916, I believe it was.
And to begin with, they were very well equipped and staffed.
But with one graduate in 1930, I don't know.
The thing had gone down, and when I got
into pathology in 1936, to be truthful, it had gone to nothing.
It was a bunch of junk.
Why is that?
All the equipment had just gone to pot.
20 years old.
Rusted out, obsolete, what have you, torn up junk.
And that was it.
So when I began in pathology, we had no slide collection.
We had some gross specimens of old lesions, tumors, and what have you.
But they hadn't been taken care of.
The fluid had been allowed to evaporate and the specimen dry out and what have you.
So there I was.
I was to teach general pathology and special pathology.
I didn't have a thing.
not a slide.
If you wanted to show a section of acute inflammation, you didn't have a section of showing an acute inflammation.
You didn't have anything.
You had to talk about it and draw pictures on the board.
That's about the only way.
Well, in pathology, I had to do all of the autopsy work in the College of Veterinary Medicine.
Everything that came into the
to the post-mortem room was subject to my investigation.
I had to do the post on it and report on it to Dr. Marsteller or to the clinicians.
I saved all of the specimens.
I got material for sectioning.
I did all of that work myself.
I was the only one in pathology.
I had no technical help.
I did all of the sectioning and staining and so on.
I did all of the post-mortem work.
I took all the gross specimens.
I put them in museum jars on Saturdays and Sundays and so on, and nights.
And maybe you have a class in general pathology, and perhaps you're taking up the pneumonias.
You just had an old cow or some animal that died and she had pneumonia.
I don't know.
Maybe what kind you have to determine.
So you've sectioned the tissue.
You've made a class set.
And you run down to class with this couple of trays of slides with the balsam still fresh and the cover slips almost floating.
Tell them to be very careful with these slides.
I've just made them.
So we studied whatever that was.
Well, our students had very little background in normal microscopic structure of tissues, histology.
Had very little training, because that was in the Department of Anatomy.
And evidently, they had nothing there either.
No slides.
Maybe they, well, Dr. Mundink came that year.
Well, he didn't come until,
Well, it was in the late 30s.
But anyway, he tried to make some slides.
But they were overstained, burnt up, not very good.
But anyway, I had to make up histology sections as well, normal tissues, as well as the abnormal.
And I had to teach them the normal first and then show them the abnormalities.
So that's the way the pathology went.
I think that's the only way to teach histology, actually.
In other words, during the middle 1930s, you had a real dearth of supplies at the school.
Do you know what my budget was?
No.
$500 a year.
Really?
That's all?
And I was the only staff member in pathology.
I had no technical help whatsoever.
And that technical help thing went on for 15 years.
It wasn't until in the 1950s that I got technical help.
Up to that time, I did everything myself.
Well, is that what the main difference between there and the University of Michigan?
Did they have money?
They had the money.
Because they didn't have the money that Michigan State had.
Right.
Because Michigan State was like University of Texas.
They were in the capital city.
They got the money.
And the University of Michigan was like A&M.
We got the hind tit.
That was it.
And so that's the way poor old A&M was.
We didn't have anything to work with.
And back in those days, we had in the administration what I've always termed the button shoe boys.
Can you explain that one?
I think I'm going to like it.
Well, the Button Shoe Boys were from the old school.
And you were judged as an administrator by the way you carried on your appropriation, your budget, and you turned money back at the end of the year.
Oh, really?
Yeah.
You could do with what they dished out to you and then turn a little back
That was about the way it was, or the way I thought it was, anyhow.
We didn't have anything to work with, and if you got anything, you almost had to fight somebody for it.
And as far as equipment went, in pathology, it was the same way in anatomy when I went there.
Dr. Francis had bought five little old high school microscopes.
I think he paid $35 a piece for them.
And that's all we had in the way of microscopes.
And you had to beg, borrow, and steal from other departments microscopes enough for the group, for the class.
Tables, kitchen tables, just plain old kitchen tables.
Chairs, old cane bottom chairs that you got out of the basement.
They'd been thrown away.
We had no air conditioning in the summer classes or in the spring or the hot days in the fall.
All the windows were open.
We had all male in the class, no females.
I said, just take your shirts off and strip down to the waist.
Really?
Right in class?
In class.
It was too hot.
And even at that, you're trying to do microscopic work, and the perspiration is dripping off your elbow.
You're sitting there.
How can you work in that condition?
It's like being in a boiler room.
It'd be better out there in the shade of a tree.
And that's the way it was at Texas A&M.
Well, when did they get electricity for electric fans and things like that?
Well, they had the electricity then.
But they didn't have the money for the fans?
They sure didn't have a fan.
Only the president had a fan in his office.
That's the same way when I was yelling my head off for air conditioning when we were putting up the new veterinary hospital out over there.
And Reese Spence was sitting there with us, going over the plans.
And I said, well, are we going to have air conditioning in this new setup?
Oh, he hit the ceiling.
Why, even Mr. Gilchrist's office isn't air conditioned.
I never had air conditioning when I was at Purdue.
So they didn't air condition.

I said, well, Mr. Spence, if you were in business in Bryan, Texas, say you were in a haberdashery, and here's another haberdashery right next to you, and he's air conditioned, who would get to business if you were not air conditioned?
I said, that guy'd get all the business and he'd run you out.
And I said, it's the same way right now.
Sam Houston University over there.
When was this?
This is in the 50s when they were building that?
Yeah, this was in the 50s.
So they have air conditioning over there in their dormitories in the summertime.
And our students are going to Sam Houston in the summertime.
Sure, I don't blame them.
Not over here in these dives that we roast them.
Come out parboiled.
But you know, they did not air condition that new set up.
And it wasn't until several years later that they went in there and then they found out that the duct system was too small to accommodate air conditioning.
They have to tear out all the ducts and punch the buildings all full of holes and enlarge their
Addicts and so on for ducks and what have you.
Then we got, for several hundred thousand dollars more, we got air conditioning.
Even though over there in that new setup, I had a great big room for histology.
I was in anatomy then.
This was to be air conditioned.
No windows.
And only one door into the hallway.
This was to be a dark room laboratory, because I used a projector and projected the slides on the screen for them to study.
This was one from their set, see?
So that when they began to study it, they had already been over it with me.
And they knew where to look for what and where.
So we finally got two great big old three-foot fans.
and set them at different places in the room so it'd stir up the air and blow you out of your wig off.
But anyhow, they finally put me a five-ton unit in the ceiling in the back of that room.
That was before the remainder of the building was air-conditioned.
I raised so much chain about it.
And then you'd almost freeze them out.
Right, right.
trying to get that thing regulated in any way.
Let's go back for a minute to when you were a student in the vet school.
Who were your favorite instructors?
Well, my favorite instructors were Dr. Burns in physiology.
Dr. Burns was always very thorough.
He was tough as a boot.
Oh, he was.
But he was thorough.
What kind of person was he besides just being tough?
Well, he was approachable because he was an Aggie.
Burns was an Aggie and I think he sort of acted like a senior among underclassmen.
He had that discipline.
It's just like our Army officers, the old Aggie Army officers.
They had that discipline.
They carried themselves well, and they proved it in World War II.
Dr. Leonard.
Dr. Leonard was another, and Dr. Dunn, the old boy I worked for in pathology.
Those fellas.
Did you have Mark Francis?
I had Mark Francis.
Yeah, he was a favorite.
But I just had him in anatomy.
What kind of teacher was he?
He was very good.
Dr. Francis was deaf as a post.
He couldn't hear himself talk.
I've heard that from others, too.
He was a comical person.
I heard.
And that meant that he talked more than anybody else.
Is that true?
Yeah.
He had a good sense of humor?
He had a very good sense of humor.
I remember one time in anatomy, he was embalming, trying to get an old mule down so he could embalm him.
And he had wet the floor so he could throw this old mule.
He got the floor real slippery and this old mule couldn't stand up on it.
It falls by himself.
He wasn't shot.
Dr. Francis had on some rubber boots.
And these rubber boots were pretty slick on the bottom.
And his feet went out from under him.
And he hit the ground, hit that concrete floor, kabam.
But he jumped up right away.
Of course, we all ran over to him to pick him up.
But he got up before we got there.
There's a little lesson in that.
So whenever you want to throw an old mule, you just wet the floor.
That's the way Dr. Francis was.
I went in his office one day.
He had just given an examination.
He had a pile of papers there on his desk.
I said, Dr. Francis, when are you going to grade our papers?
Well, he said, I'll tell you.
And he picked up those papers and he put them in one of the drawers of his desk and threw an old iron horseshoe in there on top of them.
And then he stomped on it with his foot a couple of times
Slammed the drawer.
Said, if you'll notice, in the college regulations, they say that you must give examinations.
But they don't say one word about ever grading them.
And he just grinned and looked at me.
And he never did grade them.
Really?
He says, you know, I never did flunk but one boy.
And I learned my lesson.
Said, you know that fool is a millionaire today?
I guess he should have flunked more of them, boy.
I would have been a millionaire.
Maybe he should have flunked you.
I never had any trouble with old Mark.
He was a good old boy.
He had a wonderful collection there.
It was built into a museum.
He and Dr. Ball.
Dr. Ball spent many years of his life in getting fossil remains of fern leaves and such out of the old clay banks on the Brazos River and what have you.
And he spent innumerable hours working on those babies and getting them.
And the old biology building, torn down many years ago,
The upstairs hallway ran the whole length of the building, almost.
And both sides of the hall, cases, glass top cases with all these archaeological specimens that he had worked out in.
He had them all labeled and everything.
